reviewText: I couldn't make it all the way through this one. Danny Trejo is some kind of shaman with mystical healing powers (you can tell that from the poster, right?). Bad acting, weak direction.

This is a strange movie. It starts out very depressing. It continues with some excitement that draws you in but it has a very strange ending that I did not understand. The main redeeming aspect of this movie is the female lead Krystal Vee, who is quite a beauty.
I am not to sure about this movie I haven't finished it yet. I am kinda lost. I like Danny Trejo and GaryDaniels, but this is just plain strange.

No subtitles for those who want or need them. In fact, not even a menu -  just the play option or previews from the studio selling more of the same cheap productions. If you like cheap wood bead bracelets and necklaces and candles as your props then this movie is for you. Usual plot of Thai mercenaries led by some English speaking white bad guy (Gary Daniels) as they walk into a remote village and start shooting anything that moves while they look for a few females to sell in the sex trade. Danny Trejo in a stereotypic role as a Native or Hispanic with some touching healing powers. He touches a heavily eye scarred woman and the scars disappear; she suddenly sees and her response is "Thank you" in an emotional tone similar to someone thanking the waiter for bringing their order. People die and Trejo brings them back to life with a few dreamy dead walking around in paradise scenes. This other world special effect done by washing out the image.
Daniels in his usual stereotypic role as the bad guy as he chases down his stolen prostitution and drugs related money. Would you be surprised that he gets it in the end.

The is nothing like a "bad" Danny Trejo movie. And when I say "bad" I mean "good." Unfortunately this is just a bad Danny Trejo movie with no quotation marks. Danny plays an Eastern holy man/healer who likes flowers. He gets killed in the first scene, but unlike the movie, he doesn't completely die. He can't pass over because there is still work to do, so he occasionally resurrects and helps others along the way.

Danny is killed because his peaceful village, where young girls bathe topless in the stream, is raided by Gary Daniels to abduct girls for the sex trade. Meanwhile, John Edward Lee is getting ready to die and has a brief case full of money. He wants a woman. Together Danny and Lee fight against the bad guys (with some police help) to save Nana (Krystal Vee).

The film is rather boring. While there is killing, there are not any of the "walking tall" action one would expect in a Trejo film. This is far from a grindhouse, although it makes you think it started out as one. A rather lame role for Trejo in this weak action-drama. The film takes place in Pali, an imaginary Asian city/country near India. Might be an interesting film for Buddhists who are Trejo fans.

Lazarus Papers Most of the commentary I read is focused on the top billed actor's other work, script seemed fractured, and the explanation of some parts of the story is absent. Surprise, a "Science Fiction, Drama, Action" film can be Art Film. If you must read the spec. try -- "Art and Popular Culture", Chapter Art Film. From a perch away from "The Replacement Killers" and that big guy with a huge knife painting the walls red with blood ask what is death and if death has special rules for some people. Does love matter? Are the path's of the two characters being steered buy fate? Opening: The raider comes into the village for women to resupply brothel and slave trade -- plus anything else. The healer (Trejo) is "IN" and a line has formed. The healer is using the gift to restore eyesight to a grandmother and he sees the event; "his death". The top/down camera work plus ground level camera pan with long zoom give scenes depth. Supernatural label fit? Sure. I'll call a line of dead people walking across water to somewhere that term. What I like about the healer is the problem of a healer who cannot die, he needs to die so he can be with his dead wife. The clues to how healer Art Film expects you to keep up. There are action scenes and fighting, and cop on the trail of the raider. The DVD for this film is a good idea.

This mishmash of a movie is worth watching just to see Danny Trejo as an angelic healer.  The perceptual dissonance of that fierce face and demeanor recruited to play such a sensitive character is fascinating to watch.  Other than that, this film feels like it's missing a huge chunk of backstory. Yes, it's called the Lazarus Papers, but nowhere in the movie is there a clue as to what those papers are referring to.  The script is badly written IMHO  and the actors seem a little perplexed as to where or why the story is going where it goes--which is all over the place. Sometimes you feel you've got a bead on it, and then some other new element comes in a topples your conclusions.  But it's not a challenge to watch (like Cloud Atlas, or Vanilla Sky), it's just not got any guts to it--as though the movie was about the making of another movie.  Again, this would be 1 or 2 stars, but Trejo is the diamond in the rough here, which got me to it being "OK"....

I loved the story and expected it to be a low budget film so I didn't mind that the actors were unknown for the most part or that the quality of the filming and stunts were sort of plain-Jane. If I wanted to watch what everyone else watches--strictly box office hits--I would have watched something I had seen before. This story is creative and the story telling was straight-forward and I could follow along with it easily. I had no idea what to expect for the ending, but that made it worth watching for me.
I wish more people saw things the way I do, but I know for certain that I am less critical than most, and I also can't find someone that has similar interests as me that I didn't make. With that said, I genuinely hope my review is helpful to other viewers, and I may just give the other lowly-rated movies a go now that I see the past reviewers may've had too high of expectations for what they were about to view.

Watching these movies starring Mr. Trejo and knowing that he prefers to be killed off, this one was quite a surprise. When he gets killed off the first time within about 15 minutes from the start of the movie, I figured that it was yet another "cameo" role for him.  However, I was happy to see that he not only appears many times through out the movie, he gets to be killed off several times!  It centers around Nana and Lonnie, who meet after Nana was kidnapped and held in the sex trade and is HIV positive and makes her escape. Lonnie is literally in his final days of life and neither wants to die alone.  Of course they are the romantic interests in this film.  Sebastian Riker (Gary Daniels) is the arch villain, evil to the core (why are the villains now all from the UK or Australia?), with Bai Ling as the evil and perverted "madam" of the operation who actually is  "Mister" as in the movie "Transamerica" or "The Crying Game". Also, I was quite surprised to see a young man that appeared to be a dead ringer for Forrest Whitaker but without the left-sided micro-opthalmia (a smaller eye).  Turned out it was Damon Whitaker and must be related. He did an excellent job. It has some beautiful settings, and amazing scenery, and the story is very endearing and heart-warming without being too blood-spattering.  This one will go in the "Trejo" collection for multiple watchings. Although this was no "star wars" or "Schindler's List" I believe it deserves a 4 star rating because it was a good story and held my interest.  Also, it proved that no matter how old Mr. Trejo gets, he'll still look good even with gray streaks in his hair and a gray mustache!
